Welcome to November's Turing-Roche newsletter! Here you can find what's new in the Turing-Roche strategic partnership and opportunities, events and news from both The Alan Turing Institute and Roche.

Our [five year partnership](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FSy78_51x_PVPOmcYHnHlew&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525915887595%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=w9D4L0B0zy74uk6MlcE6DiqxHU4JLooigqsbOLSASqc%3D&reserved=0) was set up officially in June 2021 following a successful [Data Study Group](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FUKBxnfL5yVJaDCAt-P5AVg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525915887595%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=MQpAfHFUt1Dqsm6Tozq8GsQ5d3Tmh76ioU9bozVk1rk%3D&reserved=0) and a 12 week research project on lung cancer treatment. Our 'North Star' is **to enable the generation of insights to better understand patient and disease heterogeneity and its relevance to clinical outcomes at an unprecedented level of precision in order to improve clinical care. **

We will be covering multiple activities over the five years to work towards our North Star, as well as building strong connections and collaborations between the Alan Turing Institute, Roche and the wider community.

If you have anything you'd like featured in a future newsletter then please get in touch with Vicky Hellon, Community Manager for the partnership at <vhellon@turing.ac.uk>

If you would like to share this newsletter with relevant colleagues please direct them to sign-up [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F9vQgVDIDqjwI56u6AzeM_A&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525915887595%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=nmver4BaCQHXRaNeYlku7xEislXKWSRaLPSs44nXlO0%3D&reserved=0).

### The Turing Way guide launches new chapter on Machine Learning Model Licenses

The [Turing Way](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPXZPLUY5Y3lFOHlESHZOVmQyNGZxdXlIZ3JDNDBRRm1LYTBSQkJjNWN2THJGSlR2VDJEcUhSUGdfcDhEMU1QRHMmcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi01MmJjYzk0Mjk0ZDE0YTRhODg5MjNjMTNkNjgzMjQ4MiZlc2lkPTRkMGE4MDFmLTE3NTktZWQxMS05NTYyLTAwMjI0ODNmNzIzMSJ9%2FNo0kq195aGCknNZDpUm_nw&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916043896%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Lz%2FZTVNf5XLqNtu3lz6%2BBzwIT8Aq9GDLLeqSz3t6Wyw%3D&reserved=0) is an open-source community-driven guide to reproducible, ethical, inclusive, and collaborative data science, aiming to provide information that data scientists in academia, industry, government and the third sector need to ensure their work is reproducible. The guide recently launched a new chapter on [Machine Learning Model Licenses](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FmN6ojiXimPWNCEcQExdr3A&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916043896%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=8EU%2FWFpHrCuU4PXAHdu5lCC%2Btfxmo4UPDBaIpNwYDII%3D&reserved=0) which we hope will be of interest. The Turing Way content is ever-evolving and is open for anyone to contribute to (particularly keen for more industry contributors!) If you are interested in contributing or finding out more please contact Vicky Hellon at <vhellon@turing.ac.uk>

### Roche Job Opportunities: PHC Senior Data Scientist and Global HTA Evidence Lead

Two relevant vacancies are open at Roche. They are hiring at Senior Data Scientist to join the personalised healthcare (PHC) Data, Analytics and Imaging group. The scientist will collaborate with peers to develop evidence generation strategies, identify evidence gaps, design and execute studies, implement analyses and develop algorithms that support the PHC product portfolio. How to apply [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2Fpx4MroZSjHa8PIBVJ7FsHg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916043896%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=L9os7vVj5azDFX1bevxDzEMqzufU2GzoLGff9tUYzBc%3D&reserved=0).

The Global HTA (Health Technology Assessment) Evidence Lead role is based in Basel. The successful applicant will work with colleagues across Roche to develop the HTA Evidence strategies and packages used by payers supporting Health Technology Assessments which determine access to Roche's innovative offerings.They will support both the pre-launch and launch stage of the reimbursement process and provide expertise required for the preparation of evidentiary plans and their application within HTA / reimbursement dossiers as well as more broadly to implement access and commercialization strategies. More info and how to apply [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPXZPLUY5Y3lFOHlESHZOVmQyNGZxdXlIZ3JDNDBRRm1LYTBSQkJjNWN2THJGSlR2VDJEcUhSUGdfcDhEMU1QRHMmcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi01MmJjYzk0Mjk0ZDE0YTRhODg5MjNjMTNkNjgzMjQ4MiZlc2lkPTRkMGE4MDFmLTE3NTktZWQxMS05NTYyLTAwMjI0ODNmNzIzMSJ9%2FCeG6ut72ZYNp3tsV4tNqqg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916043896%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=jl%2FVXDmg8AlFqIwoMAzSURShuVKf7tIvqI9TKCSSSUA%3D&reserved=0).

### New Turing Interest Groups Launched

The Turing Institute has launched nine new interest groups this month (including groups on Health Equity, Meta-learning for Multimodal Data and Novel Data Linkages for Health and Wellbeing). Interest Groups aim to promote research collaboration, share knowledge, and communicate emerging scientific concepts to the wider Institute and beyond, around a shared area of interest in data science and AI. Anyone is welcome to join the groups so we would encourage our community to do so! You can find the new groups and other current ones [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FX5FvLsNZjfpFHGbN79o7jg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916043896%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=qaDRl6BQHaWqe1mtOGYdYRyw89GbVyDBU8olKqAp1B4%3D&reserved=0)- each group webpage has instructions on how to join.

### AI for Multiple Long-Term Conditions Research Support Facility Seminar: Developing and Publishing Code for Trusted Research Environments (TREs)

**08 November 2022**

The RSF monthly seminar series is organised by the AI for multiple long-term conditions: Research Support Facility (RSF), and showcases talks from leading voices in data science, AI, healthcare and those with lived experience of multiple long-term conditions (MLTC). This month they will be joined by Ed Chalstrey, Research Data Scientist at the Turing Institute. The session will look at developing and publishing code within TREs and draws on lessons from the Wales Multimorbidity Machine Learning Project. More info and registration [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2F1iGl0OhqeJynI5W2gHkYTA&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916356401%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=J71HlViwBDN%2F237LMM4%2BFUv%2FS2oghiFVUn3vsZ4ma%2FY%3D&reserved=0).

### Statistical Methods for Health Equity Series: Using machine learning to increase equity in healthcare and public health

**10 November 2022**

The Statistical Methods for Health Equity Series is a monthly online series co-hosted by the Data Science for Health Equity community, the Alan Turing Institute, and the Department of Statistical Science at University College London. For their second talk in the series, they will be welcoming Dr Emma Pierson from Cornell University, who will be presenting on 'Using machine learning to increase equity in healthcare and public health'. ### Hybrid Modelling Workshop

**30 November 2022**

Hybrid modelling that integrates 'white box' (mechanistic, physics-based) and 'black box' (machine learning) is becoming common as it could combine the best of both worlds. This one-day workshop aims to bring together communities from both paradigms to interact, learn from one another and foster collaboration. There will also be a session to discuss the challenges of hybrid modelling and how best to address them. The workshop is being held in-person at the University of Birmingham and there is also a virtual option. Find out more [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FYyS8y0n3Rvr6G_lRk4kUuA&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916356401%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=pCjzDKpXP1zTyTcggkJseIw4akyM4RB%2FPlN7LlACouA%3D&reserved=0).

## Publication of the Month

![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/patrick-tomasso-oaqk7qqnh_c-unsplash2.jpg)

### Stop explaining black box machine learning models for high stakes decisions and use interpretable models instead**

November's publication of the month is from Cynthia Rudin, Professor of Computer Science and Engineering at Duke University. This [2019 paper](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%%2FqveGHPa14hoVV6fsTh9tDA&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916356401%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=CBSNue%2FATQGjunHbIRPX2aa49XmVtbVq7TBkuJ79%2BNU%3D&reserved=0) published in Nature Machine Intelligence (preprint version [here](https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Felink.turing.ac.uk%2Fc%2F7%_X2NsZGVlPXZPLUY5Y3lFOHlESHZOVmQyNGZxdXlIZ3JDNDBRRm1LYTBSQkJjNWN2THJGSlR2VDJEcUhSUGdfcDhEMU1QRHMmcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi01MmJjYzk0Mjk0ZDE0YTRhODg5MjNjMTNkNjgzMjQ4MiZlc2lkPTRkMGE4MDFmLTE3NTktZWQxMS05NTYyLTAwMjI0ODNmNzIzMSJ9%2FNOXTcR_4V5a4CVfotyzOvg&data=05%7C01%7Cvhellon%40turing.ac.uk%7Ce563328bdcec4ea7873508dabe4ad7e0%7C4395f4a7e4554f958a9f1fbaef6384f9%7C0%7C0%7C638031525916356401%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=IimysQHARSA6ZenHS4qjD6F2Sp4OSec3QkmnNphLvWo%3D&reserved=0)) advocates that the use of simpler and inherently interpretable predictive models in high-stakes applications like healthcare might be better than opting for highly complex black box models, whose explanations might end up being difficult to interpret. This publication has been particularly useful for the partnership team when focusing current thinking around our predictive modelling research theme, especially in the context of "usable explainability" being important for AI in healthcare to be deemed transparent and trustworthy, and thus increase the chances of being adopted in a practical setting.
